<p>I’m a teammate of <a class="mention" href="/u/somerandomuser">@somerandomuser</a>. Thank you for your help! Just to clarify, the full range value is multiplied by voltage-reading/5V right? To scale to 3.3 V shouldn’t we multiply by 5/3.3 to cancel the denominators? Am I misunderstanding?</p>
<p>Once again, thanks!</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-14T03:17:16.279Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":48,"readers_count":47,"score":14.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":430163,"topic_slug":"questions-about-the-analogpotentiometer-class","display_username":"Ryan Elchahal","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":13575,"username":"Peter_Johnson","name":"Peter Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":54521,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/questions-about-the-analogpotentiometer-class/430163/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3164191,"name":"Peter Johnson","username":"Peter_Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png","created_at":"2023-03-14T03:40:05.968Z","cooked":"<p>Here’s the code that does the scaling:</p><aside class="onebox githubblob" data-onebox-src="https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/AnalogPotentiometer.java#L126-L127">
  <header class="source">

      <a href="https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/AnalogPotentiometer.java#L126-L127" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com</a>
  </header>

  <article class="onebox-body">
    <h4><a href="https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/AnalogPotentiometer.java#L126-L127" target="_blank" rel="noopener">wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/AnalogPotentiometer.java#L126-L127</a></h4>



    <pre class="onebox"><code class="lang-java">
      <ol class="start lines" start="126" style="counter-reset: li-counter 125 ;">
          <li>return (m_analogInput.getAverageVoltage() / RobotController.getVoltage5V()) * m_fullRange</li>
          <li>    + m_offset;</li>
      </ol>
    </code></pre>



  </article>

  <div class="onebox-metadata">


  </div>

  <div style="clear: both"></div>
</aside>

<p>So yes, you’re correct re: the fullScale value (it should be 270 * 5.0 / 3.3).  Note the offset is just added in at the end so should be in degrees, and not scaled.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-14T03:40:05.968Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":45,"readers_count":44,"score":19.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":430163,"topic_slug":"questions-about-the-analogpotentiometer-class","display_username":"Peter Johnson","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/AnalogPotentiometer.java#L126-L127","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"allwpilib/AnalogPotentiometer.java at main · wpilibsuite/allwpilib · GitHub","clicks":2}],"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":54521,"username":"Relch06","name":"Ryan Elchahal","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/r/b2d939/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":13575,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Volunteer WPILib Developer, CSA"},"post_url":"/t/questions-about-the-analogpotentiometer-class/430163/4","custom_user_title":"Volunteer WPILib Developer, CSA","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3164299,"name":"","username":"somerandomuser","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/b2d939/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-03-14T12:34:23.605Z","cooked":"<p>Thanks for your help! Everything here makes sense. However, one question: shouldn’t our full range be 93, not 270?  In other words, does the full range parameter of the potentiometer class represent the entire range of our potentiometer or our desired range.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-14T12:36:03.767Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":30,"readers_count":29,"score":11.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":430163,"topic_slug":"questions-about-the-analogpotentiometer-class","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":13575,"username":"Peter_Johnson","name":"Peter Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":52621,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/questions-about-the-analogpotentiometer-class/430163/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3164328,"name":"Peter Johnson","username":"Peter_Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png","created_at":"2023-03-14T13:28:29.612Z","cooked":"<p>It represents the entire range.</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2023-03-14T13:28:29.612Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":